    oneLiner: "Pope Leo XIII's 1891 encyclical that launched modern Catholic Social Teaching by defending workers' rights against both unbridled capitalism and socialism.",
    body: "Rerum Novarum ('Of New Things'), issued by Pope Leo XIII in 1891, is the foundational document of modern Catholic Social Teaching. Written during the Industrial Revolution, it addressed the misery of the working class while rejecting both laissez-faire capitalism and Marxist socialism as inadequate solutions. Leo XIII affirmed the right to private property as rooted in natural law while insisting that ownership carries social obligations. He defended the right of workers to form associations (unions), demanded just wages sufficient to support a family, condemned the exploitation of child and women's labor, and called on the state to protect the vulnerable without overstepping into socialism. The encyclical established key principles that would shape all subsequent social teaching: the dignity of labor, the rights of workers, the limits of state power, and the obligation of the wealthy to care for the poor. It sparked a tradition of papal social encyclicals that continues to the present day.",
