    oneLiner: "Catholic Social Teaching holds that men and women are equal in dignity but different and complementary in their embodiment, gifts, and vocations.",
    body: "Catholic teaching on gender complementarity affirms the equal dignity of men and women as persons made in the image of God while recognizing that sexual difference is not incidental but constitutive of the human person. The body is not a mere instrument of the soul but an integral dimension of personal identity. Man and woman, in their bodily difference, are oriented toward each other in a complementarity that finds its fullest expression in marriage and family life but extends to all dimensions of social existence. Pope John Paul II's Theology of the Body and his apostolic letter Mulieris Dignitatem (1988) provide the most developed magisterial treatment, arguing that the 'feminine genius'—characterized by receptivity, sensitivity to the person, and a capacity for self-giving—makes an irreplaceable contribution to the Church and society. The Church opposes both the subordination of women (which denies equal dignity) and gender ideology (which denies the significance of sexual difference), proposing instead a vision of reciprocal enrichment.",
    example: "Pope John Paul II argued that Mary's 'fiat'—her free, total 'yes' to God's plan—represents the highest human response to God and reveals the dignity and vocation of every woman. Mary's receptivity is not passivity but the most powerful form of human cooperation with divine grace.",
    whyItMatters: "In a culture polarized between patriarchal oppression and the denial of sexual difference, Catholic teaching on complementarity offers a third way that honors the equal dignity of men and women while celebrating rather than erasing the meaning of their bodily difference.",
