    id: "cst-ecological-conversion",
    term: "Ecological Conversion",
    category: "social-teaching",
    tags: ["ecology", "conversion", "Laudato Si'", "Francis", "creation"],
    oneLiner: "Ecological conversion is the interior transformation that leads Christians to recognize care for creation as an integral part of their faith, not an optional add-on.",
    body: "The concept of ecological conversion was introduced by Pope John Paul II and developed extensively by Pope Francis in Laudato Si' (2015). It refers to a profound interior change—a conversion of heart—in which Christians come to see the natural world not merely as a resource to be exploited but as God's creation to be respected, protected, and cherished. This conversion has several dimensions: gratitude for the gift of creation; recognition that environmental destruction harms the poor most severely; awareness of our interconnection with all living creatures; a contemplative capacity to see God's presence in nature; and a willingness to change lifestyles that are ecologically destructive. Pope Francis argues that the ecological crisis is inseparable from the social crisis: the same mindset that exploits the earth also exploits the poor. Therefore, ecological conversion must include a commitment to justice, simplicity, and solidarity. It is not merely an ethical program but a spiritual transformation that flows from a living encounter with the Creator through his creation.",
    example: "A parish that undertakes ecological conversion might install solar panels, reduce waste, source food locally for parish events, incorporate creation themes into homilies and faith formation, and advocate for environmental policy—all flowing from a deepened sense of gratitude for God's creation rather than from mere political activism.",
    whyItMatters: "Ecological conversion bridges the gap between environmentalism and spirituality, showing that care for creation is not a secular political issue but an authentic expression of Catholic faith that flows from gratitude, reverence, and justice.",
