    id: "cst-water-human-right",
    term: "Water as a Human Right",
    category: "social-teaching",
    tags: ["water", "access", "right", "privatization", "common good"],
    oneLiner: "Catholic Social Teaching affirms that access to safe, clean drinking water is a basic human right that must not be denied to anyone by poverty or privatization.",
    body: "Pope Francis in Laudato Si' (2015) declared that 'access to safe drinkable water is a basic and universal human right, since it is essential to human survival and, as such, is a condition for the exercise of other human rights.' Approximately two billion people worldwide lack access to safely managed drinking water, and water scarcity is projected to worsen due to climate change, population growth, and pollution. Catholic Social Teaching opposes the unrestricted privatization and commodification of water, which can place this essential resource beyond the reach of the poor. While the Church does not oppose all private involvement in water management, it insists that water is part of the universal destination of goods and that no person or community may be denied access due to inability to pay. The Church calls for responsible water governance, investment in infrastructure to deliver clean water to underserved communities, protection of watersheds and aquifers, and international cooperation on transboundary water resources.",
    example: "In Bolivia in 2000, the privatization of the water system in Cochabamba led to dramatic price increases that put clean water beyond the reach of the poorest families, triggering mass protests (the 'Water War'). Catholic Social Teaching would have predicted this outcome: when a basic necessity is treated purely as a market commodity, the poor suffer first.",
    whyItMatters: "Water scarcity is one of the defining crises of the twenty-first century. Catholic Social Teaching provides a moral framework for ensuring that this most basic human need is governed by the common good rather than by market forces alone.",
