    id: "cst-fair-trade",
    term: "Fair Trade",
    category: "social-teaching",
    tags: ["fair trade", "justice", "trade", "producers", "just price"],
    oneLiner: "Fair trade embodies Catholic Social Teaching principles by ensuring that producers in developing countries receive just prices for their goods and work in dignified conditions.",
    body: "The fair trade movement, though not exclusively Catholic in origin, embodies key principles of Catholic Social Teaching: the just wage, the dignity of work, solidarity, and the preferential option for the poor. Fair trade certification systems guarantee that producers in developing countries receive a minimum price that covers the cost of sustainable production, along with a social premium for community development projects. Workers are guaranteed safe conditions, the right to organize, and freedom from forced or child labor. Environmental standards promote sustainable farming practices. Catholic Social Teaching has long insisted on 'just price'—a concept rooted in Aquinas—that recognizes the moral dimension of economic exchange. When global commodity markets force coffee farmers, cocoa growers, or garment workers to sell their labor or products below the cost of a dignified livelihood, the market has failed morally even if it functions efficiently. Many Catholic parishes, schools, and religious orders have adopted fair trade purchasing policies as a practical expression of solidarity.",
    example: "A Catholic parish that switches to fair trade coffee for its after-Mass fellowship ensures that the farmers who grew the beans received a price sufficient to support their families, send their children to school, and invest in their communities—a small but concrete act of solidarity that connects Sunday worship to Monday's global economy.",
    whyItMatters: "Fair trade provides an accessible, practical way for Catholics to align their daily consumption choices with the principles of Catholic Social Teaching, demonstrating that economic justice is not just a matter for governments but for every consumer.",
