    id: "cst-catholic-social-movements",
    term: "Catholic Social Movements",
    category: "social-teaching",
    tags: ["movements", "activism", "lay", "organizing", "justice"],
    oneLiner: "Throughout history, Catholic Social Teaching has inspired diverse social movements—from labor unions to cooperatives to human rights campaigns—that put the Church's principles into action.",
    body: "Catholic Social Teaching has given rise to a rich array of social movements that translate principles into practice. In the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries, Catholic labor movements—inspired by Rerum Novarum—organized workers across Europe, Latin America, and North America. Catholic Action movements mobilized the laity to transform their workplaces and communities according to the 'see-judge-act' method championed by Cardinal Joseph Cardijn. The Focolare, Sant'Egidio, and L'Arche movements address solidarity, peace, and disability rights respectively. In Latin America, base ecclesial communities applied Catholic Social Teaching at the grassroots level, empowering the poor to read the Gospel in light of their social reality. Catholic rural life movements and credit unions (Desjardins in Canada, Raiffeisen cooperatives in Europe) applied the principle of subsidiarity to economic life. The global network of Caritas Internationalis coordinates Catholic charitable and development work in over 200 countries. These movements demonstrate that Catholic Social Teaching is not merely an academic exercise but a living tradition that generates concrete action for justice.",
    example: "The Young Christian Workers (YCW), founded by Cardinal Joseph Cardijn in Belgium in 1924, trained millions of young workers to analyze their workplace conditions in light of the Gospel and take concrete action for justice—a method ('see-judge-act') that influenced the entire tradition of Catholic Social Teaching.",
    whyItMatters: "Catholic social movements are the proof that the Church's social teaching is not just a collection of documents but a living tradition that transforms lives and societies. They offer models and inspiration for Catholics seeking to put their faith into action today.",
